the mexico unit of volkswagen and its 9800 unionized workers have reached an agreement for a shorter workweek that will save 2000 jobs the union agreed to accept a four day workweek and an overall temporary pay cut for the 20 percent of the workers with the least seniority the other 80 percent of the work force will lose pay just for the day not worked the plant in puebla about 75 miles east of mexico city is vw 's only north american plant and exports about 80 percent of its production earlier this year volkswagen said that reduced demand in the united states would force it to cut the jobs vw management has long been seeking a more flexible workweek from its mexican union the plant produces the new beetle and the jetta models and will begin making the new generation of the jetta called the bora in 2005 elisabeth malkin nyt

